TODO()` in the agent layer. While the nolint comment and explanation are appropriate, and `WriteSession` is marked as a \"Legacy\" method in the interface documentation, this leaves one path where cancellation/timeout from the caller is not respected. The downstream functions `runOpenCodeSessionDelete` and `runOpenCodeImport` execute external commands (`opencode session delete`, `opencode import`) that should ideally honor parent cancellation.\n\n*Suggested fix:* Add `context.Context` to the `WriteSession` interface as part of this changeset, or create a follow-up tracking issue. Since this is a broad interface change with many callers, a follow-up is acceptable.\n\n**2. `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/hooks_claudecode_posttodo.go:25-26` -- `handleClaudeCodePostTodoFromReader` re-reads stdin from `os.Stdin` (low severity, pre-existing)**\n\n```go\nfunc handleClaudeCodePostTodo(ctx context.Context) error {\n    return handleClaudeCodePostTodoFromReader(ctx, os.Stdin)\n}\n```\n\n`handleClaudeCodePostTodo(ctx)` is called from `hook_registry.go:150`, which already parsed the hook event from `cmd.InOrStdin()`. The `handleClaudeCodePostTodo` function then re-reads `os.Stdin` directly. Since `ParseHookEvent` for PostTodo returns `(nil, nil)` (line 59 of `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/claudecode/lifecycle.go`), the stdin stream has NOT been consumed by the event parser. However, this relies on the implicit ordering: first the nil check at line 145, then the PostTodo branch at line 148 in `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go`. If future refactoring moves PostTodo into the lifecycle dispatcher, stdin would already be consumed.\n\n*Pre-existing design concern. No action needed for this PR but worth noting for future work.*\n\n### Suggestions (Consider)\n\n**1. `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/agent.go` -- Consider adding `context.Context` to more legacy methods**\n\nSeveral Agent interface methods still lack context parameters:\n- `ReadTranscript(sessionRef string) ([]byte, error)`\n- `ReassembleTranscript(chunks [][]byte) ([]byte, error)`\n- `GetSessionID(input *HookInput) string`\n- `GetSessionDir(repoPath string) (string, error)`\n- `ReadSession(input *HookInput) (*AgentSession, error)`\n- `WriteSession(session *AgentSession) error`\n\nThese are documented as \"Legacy methods (will move to optional interfaces in Phase 4).\" The current PR correctly focuses on the methods that need ctx (those that call `paths.RepoRoot`, execute external commands, or perform I/O). No action needed now, but this surfaces as a future consistency opportunity.\n\n**2. `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/claudecode/lifecycle.go:237-258` -- `waitForTranscriptFlush` could use `ctx.Done()` for cancellation**\n\nThe polling loop:\n```go\ndeadline := time.Now().Add(maxWait)\nfor time.Now().Before(deadline) {\n    if checkStopSentinel(transcriptPath, tailBytes, hookStartTime, maxSkew) {\n        return\n    }\n    time.Sleep(pollInterval)\n}\n```\n\nNow that ctx is threaded through, this loop could check `ctx.Done()` to allow early termination if the parent context is cancelled. Current behavior (3-second timeout with 50ms polls) is fine for correctness, but honoring cancellation would be a nice improvement:\n\n```go\nfor time.Now().Before(deadline) {\n    select {\n    case <-ctx.Done():\n        return\n    default:\n    }\n    if checkStopSentinel(transcriptPath, tailBytes, hookStartTime, maxSkew) {\n        return\n    }\n    time.Sleep(pollInterval)\n}\n```\n\n**3. `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/hook_registry.go:101-104` -- `IsEnabled()` still uses `context.TODO()` internally**\n\nThe hook verb command at line 102 calls:\n```go\nenabled, err := IsEnabled()\n```\n\nWhile `IsEnabled()` (defined in `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/config.go:57`) internally uses `context.TODO()` for `settings.Load()`, the cmd already has `cmd.Context()` available. Consider either passing ctx to an `IsEnabled(ctx)` variant, or accepting this as a separate follow-up since `IsEnabled` is called from many places.\n\n*Low priority -- consistent with the `GetStrategy()` call at line 113 which also uses `context.TODO()` internally. These are CLI-layer convenience functions that will likely be updated in a separate sweep.*\n\n**4. `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/cli_commands.go:17-18` -- Context layering in `runOpenCodeExport`**\n\n```go\nfunc runOpenCodeExport(ctx context.Context, sessionID string) ([]byte, error) {\n    ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(ctx, openCodeCommandTimeout)\n```\n\nThe function shadows `ctx` with the timeout-wrapped version. This is idiomatic Go and correct. The 30-second timeout is now layered on top of any deadline the caller's context already has. If the caller has a shorter deadline, the parent deadline wins. This is correct behavior -- noting that the timeout is now a maximum bound rather than a fixed bound. No change needed.\n\n### Praise\n\n- **Mechanical consistency across all three agent implementations.** The Claude Code, Gemini CLI, and OpenCode agents all receive identical treatment: `context.Context` is added as the first parameter to every interface method that needs it. The naming convention (`_ context.Context` when unused, `ctx context.Context` when used) is applied correctly throughout.\n\n- **Good judgment on where ctx is used vs unused.** Methods that genuinely use the context (e.g., `DetectPresence` calls `paths.RepoRoot(ctx)`, `InstallHooks` calls `paths.RepoRoot(ctx)`, `waitForTranscriptFlush` enriches the logging context) receive `ctx`. Methods that don't need it yet (e.g., `ParseHookEvent` in ClaudeCode and Gemini, which only parse stdin) correctly use `_ context.Context` as a placeholder for future use, while still satisfying the interface contract.\n\n- **Clean elimination of `context.Background()` from production code.** All `context.Background()` usages in the reviewed production files have been replaced with proper context propagation from `cmd.Context()`. The remaining `context.Background()` usages are exclusively in test files, which is the correct pattern.\n\n- **Proper handling of the variable name conflict in `hooks_claudecode_posttodo.go`.** The old code had `ctx := strategy.TaskStepContext{...}` which shadowed any potential `context.Context` variable. The rename to `taskStepCtx` (line 119) and `strat.SaveTaskStep(ctx, taskStepCtx)` (line 137) is clean and avoids confusion between the two `ctx` meanings.\n\n- **Thorough test updates.** Every test call site has been updated to pass `context.Background()` as the first argument, maintaining complete test coverage for the new signatures. The compile-time interface assertions (`var _ Agent = (*mockAgent)(nil)`) in test files ensure the mock implementations stay in sync.\n\n- **The `context.TODO()` annotation in `/Users/pfleidi/entire/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/opencode/opencode.go:220` is honest and well-documented.** Rather than silently passing `context.Background()`, the code uses `context.TODO()` with a clear nolint comment explaining why, signaling this is known technical debt.\n\n- **Context flows end-to-end from Cobra commands.** In `hook_registry.go` and `hooks_git_cmd.go`, context originates from `cmd.Context()` and flows through `logging.WithComponent()` and `logging.WithAgent()` enrichment before reaching agent methods. This establishes a clean pattern where all downstream logging and I/O operations can trace back to the command invocation.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n**Overall assessment: APPROVE**\n\nThis is a well-executed mechanical refactoring that threads `context.Context` through the agent layer interfaces and their call sites. The changes are:\n\n1. **Correct** -- the code compiles, all tests pass, and the context propagation is consistent from Cobra command handlers through agent interfaces to underlying system calls (`git rev-parse`, `opencode export`, etc.).\n\n2. **